   218→## 7.3.0
   219→
   220→* Add `subset(r1, r2)` method to determine if `r1` range is entirely
   221→  contained by `r2` range.
   223→## 7.2.3
   224→
   225→* Fix handling of `includePrelease` mode where version ranges like `1.0.0 -
   226→  2.0.0` would include `3.0.0-pre` and not `1.0.0-pre`.
   228→## 7.2.2
   229→
   230→* Fix bug where `2.0.0-pre` would be included in `^1.0.0` if
   231→  `includePrerelease` was set to true.
   233→## 7.2.0
   234→
   235→* Add `simplifyRange` method to attempt to generate a more human-readable
   236→  range expression that is equivalent to a supplied range, for a given set
   237→  of versions.
   239→## 7.1.2
   240→
   241→* Remove fancy lazy-loading logic, as it was causing problems for webpack
   242→  users.
   244→## 7.1.0
   245→
   246→* Add `require('semver/preload')` to load the entire module without using
   247→  lazy getter methods.
   249→## 7.0.0
   250→
   251→* Refactor module into separate files for better tree-shaking
   252→* Drop support for very old node versions, use const/let, `=>` functions,
   253→  and classes.
   255→## 6.3.0
   256→
   257→* Expose the token enum on the exports
   259→## 6.2.0
   260→
   261→* Coerce numbers to strings when passed to semver.coerce()
   262→* Add `rtl` option to coerce from right to left
   264→## 6.1.3
   265→
   266→* Handle X-ranges properly in includePrerelease mode
   268→## 6.1.2
   269→
   270→* Do not throw when testing invalid version strings
   272→## 6.1.1
   273→
   274→* Add options support for semver.coerce()
   275→* Handle undefined version passed to Range.test
   277→## 6.1.0
   278→
   279→* Add semver.compareBuild function
   280→* Support `*` in semver.intersects
   282→## 6.0
   283→
   284→* Fix `intersects` logic.
   290→## 5.7
   291→
   292→* Add `minVersion` method
   294→## 5.6
   295→
   296→* Move boolean `loose` param to an options object, with
   297→  backwards-compatibility protection.
   298→* Add ability to opt out of special prerelease version handling with
   299→  the `includePrerelease` option flag.
   301→## 5.5
   302→
   303→* Add version coercion capabilities
   305→## 5.4
   306→
   307→* Add intersection checking
   309→## 5.3
   310→
   311→* Add `minSatisfying` method
   313→## 5.2
   314→
   315→* Add `prerelease(v)` that returns prerelease components
   317→## 5.1
   318→
   319→* Add Backus-Naur for ranges
   320→* Remove excessively cute inspection methods
   322→## 5.0
   323→
   324→* Remove AMD/Browserified build artifacts
   325→* Fix ltr and gtr when using the `*` range
   326→* Fix for range `*` with a prerelease identifier
CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
     3→# Contributing
     4→
     5→## Code of Conduct
     6→
     7→All interactions in the **npm** organization on GitHub are considered to be covered by our standard [Code of Conduct](https://docs.npmjs.com/policies/conduct).
     9→## Reporting Bugs
    10→
    11→Before submitting a new bug report please search for an existing or similar report.
    17→## Pull Request Conventions
    18→
    19→### Commits
    20→
    21→We use [Conventional Commits](https://www.conventionalcommits.org/en/v1.0.0/).
    30→### Test Coverage
    31→
    32→Pull requests made against this repo will run `npm test` automatically.  Please make sure tests pass locally before submitting a PR.
    36→### Linting
    37→
    38→Linting is also done automatically once tests pass.  `npm run lintfix` will fix most linting errors automatically.
    42→## What _not_ to contribute?
    43→
    44→### Dependencies
    45→
    46→It should be noted that our team does not accept third-party dependency updates/PRs.  If you submit a PR trying to update our dependencies we will close it with or without a reference to these contribution guidelines.
    48→### Tools/Automation
    49→
    50→Our core team is responsible for the maintenance of the tooling/automation in this project and we ask contributors to not make changes to these when contributing (e.g. `.github/*`, `.eslintrc.json`, `.licensee.json`).  Most of those files also have a header at the top to remind folks they are automatically generated.  Pull requests that alter these will not be accepted.
README.md
     1→semver(1) -- The semantic versioner for npm
     3→
     4→## Install
     5→
     6→```bash
     7→npm install semver
     8→````
    10→## Usage
    11→
    12→As a node module:
   139→## Versions
   140→
   141→A "version" is described by the `v2.0.0` specification found at
   142→<https://semver.org/>.
   148→## Ranges
   149→
   150→A `version range` is a set of `comparators` that specify versions
   151→that satisfy the range.
   184→### Prerelease Tags
   185→
   186→If a version has a prerelease tag (for example, `1.2.3-alpha.3`) then
   187→it will only be allowed to satisfy comparator sets if at least one
   188→comparator with the same `[major, minor, patch]` tuple also has a
   189→prerelease tag.
   219→#### Prerelease Identifiers
   220→
   221→The method `.inc` takes an additional `identifier` string argument that
   222→will append the value of the string as a prerelease identifier:
   250→#### Prerelease Identifier Base
   251→
   252→The method `.inc` takes an optional parameter 'identifierBase' string
   253→that will let you let your prerelease number as zero-based or one-based.
   254→Set to `false` to omit the prerelease number altogether.
   255→If you do not specify this parameter, it will default to zero-based.
   279→### Advanced Range Syntax
   280→
   281→Advanced range syntax desugars to primitive comparators in
   282→deterministic ways.
   287→#### Hyphen Ranges `X.Y.Z - A.B.C`
   288→
   289→Specifies an inclusive set.
   306→#### X-Ranges `1.2.x` `1.X` `1.2.*` `*`
   307→
   308→Any of `X`, `x`, or `*` may be used to "stand in" for one of the
   309→numeric values in the `[major, minor, patch]` tuple.
   324→#### Tilde Ranges `~1.2.3` `~1.2` `~1`
   325→
   326→Allows patch-level changes if a minor version is specified on the
   327→comparator.  Allows minor-level changes if not.
   341→#### Caret Ranges `^1.2.3` `^0.2.5` `^0.0.4`
   342→
   343→Allows changes that do not modify the left-most non-zero element in the
   344→`[major, minor, patch]` tuple.  In other words, this allows patch and
   345→minor updates for versions `1.0.0` and above, patch updates for
   346→versions `0.X >=0.1.0`, and *no* updates for versions `0.0.X`.
   384→### Range Grammar
   385→
   386→Putting all this together, here is a Backus-Naur grammar for ranges,
   387→for the benefit of parser authors:
   408→## Functions
   409→
   410→All methods and classes take a final `options` object argument.  All
   411→options in this object are `false` by default.  The options supported
   412→are:
   453→### Comparison
   454→
   455→* `gt(v1, v2)`: `v1 > v2`
   456→* `gte(v1, v2)`: `v1 >= v2`
   457→* `lt(v1, v2)`: `v1 < v2`
   458→* `lte(v1, v2)`: `v1 <= v2`
   459→* `eq(v1, v2)`: `v1 == v2` This is true if they're logically equivalent,
   460→  even if they're not the same string.  You already know how to
   461→  compare strings.
   462→* `neq(v1, v2)`: `v1 != v2` The opposite of `eq`.
   463→* `cmp(v1, comparator, v2)`: Pass in a comparison string, and it'll call
   464→  the corresponding function above.  `"==="` and `"!=="` do simple
   465→  string comparison, but are included for completeness.  Throws if an
   466→  invalid comparison string is provided.
   467→* `compare(v1, v2)`: Return `0` if `v1 == v2`, or `1` if `v1` is greater, or `-1` if
   468→  `v2` is greater.  Sorts in ascending order if passed to `Array.sort()`.
   469→* `rcompare(v1, v2)`: The reverse of `compare`.  Sorts an array of versions
   470→  in descending order when passed to `Array.sort()`.
   471→* `compareBuild(v1, v2)`: The same as `compare` but considers `build` when two versions
   472→  are equal.  Sorts in ascending order if passed to `Array.sort()`.
   473→* `compareLoose(v1, v2)`: Short for `compare(v1, v2, { loose: true })`.
   474→* `diff(v1, v2)`: Returns the difference between two versions by the release type
   475→  (`major`, `premajor`, `minor`, `preminor`, `patch`, `prepatch`, or `prerelease`),
   476→  or null if the versions are the same.
   478→### Sorting
   479→
   480→* `sort(versions)`: Returns a sorted array of versions based on the `compareBuild` 
   481→  function.
   482→* `rsort(versions)`: The reverse of `sort`. Returns an array of versions based on
   483→  the `compareBuild` function in descending order.
   485→### Comparators
   486→
   487→* `intersects(comparator)`: Return true if the comparators intersect
   489→### Ranges
   490→
   491→* `validRange(range)`: Return the valid range or null if it's not valid.
   492→* `satisfies(version, range)`: Return true if the version satisfies the
   493→  range.
   494→* `maxSatisfying(versions, range)`: Return the highest version in the list
   495→  that satisfies the range, or `null` if none of them do.
   496→* `minSatisfying(versions, range)`: Return the lowest version in the list
   497→  that satisfies the range, or `null` if none of them do.
   498→* `minVersion(range)`: Return the lowest version that can match
   499→  the given range.
   500→* `gtr(version, range)`: Return `true` if the version is greater than all the
   501→  versions possible in the range.
   502→* `ltr(version, range)`: Return `true` if the version is less than all the
   503→  versions possible in the range.
   504→* `outside(version, range, hilo)`: Return true if the version is outside
   505→  the bounds of the range in either the high or low direction.  The
   506→  `hilo` argument must be either the string `'>'` or `'<'`.  (This is
   507→  the function called by `gtr` and `ltr`.)
   508→* `intersects(range)`: Return true if any of the range comparators intersect.
   509→* `simplifyRange(versions, range)`: Return a "simplified" range that
   510→  matches the same items in the `versions` list as the range specified.  Note
   511→  that it does *not* guarantee that it would match the same versions in all
   512→  cases, only for the set of versions provided.  This is useful when
   513→  generating ranges by joining together multiple versions with `||`
   514→  programmatically, to provide the user with something a bit more
   515→  ergonomic.  If the provided range is shorter in string-length than the
   516→  generated range, then that is returned.
   517→* `subset(subRange, superRange)`: Return `true` if the `subRange` range is
   518→  entirely contained by the `superRange` range.
   531→### Coercion
   532→
   533→* `coerce(version, options)`: Coerces a string to semver if possible
   558→### Clean
   559→
   560→* `clean(version)`: Clean a string to be a valid semver if possible
   576→## Constants
   577→
   578→As a convenience, helper constants are exported to provide information about what `node-semver` supports:
   580→### `RELEASE_TYPES`
   581→
   582→- major
   583→- premajor
   584→- minor
   585→- preminor
   586→- patch
   587→- prepatch
   588→- prerelease
   600→### `SEMVER_SPEC_VERSION`
   601→
   602→2.0.0
   610→## Exported Modules
   611→
